@node list "Promotion List Gadgets"
@wordwrap

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Promotion List Gadgets@{ub}@{fg text}

 @{fg highlight}1 @{fg text}[G|  Program Names  ]  
   +--------------+-++-+  
   |              |#|| |  
   |              |#||#|  
   |              |#||#|  
 @{fg highlight}2 @{fg text}|              |#|| | @{fg highlight}7@{fg text}
   |              |#|| |  
   |              |^|| |  
   |______________|V|| |  
 @{fg highlight}3 @{fg text}[  Name Gadget   ]| |  
 @{fg highlight}4 @{fg text}[   Add   ][ Delete ] @{fg highlight}5@{fg text}
 @{fg highlight}6 @{fg text}[       Select      ]  
@{jleft}
@{fg highlight}1. Promotion List Cycle Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget switches which promotion list is being displayed.  There are four lists:
@{b}· Screen Names@{ub}
    The Screen Names list contains screen titles, if a program opens a screen who's Title matches an entry in this list it is promoted.
@{b}· Program Names@{ub}
    When a program in this list opens any screen, ModePro promotes the screen.
@{b}· ScreenModes@{ub}
    When a screen is opened using a screen mode in the list, it is promoted.  
@{b}· Public Screens@{ub}
    If a public screen is requested that matches an entry in this list, ModePro will create that screen, closing it when neccesary.  Also see @{"Creating a Public Screen Entry" link createpubscreens}.

@{b}@{i}Note:@{ub}@{ui}  If a screen that is to be opened matches entries in multiple lists, ModePro will seach the lists in this order Screen Names, Program Names, and then ScreenModes.

@{fg highlight}2. Promotion List@{fg text}
    This list displays the entry names in the list selected by the above gadget.  Click on an entry to edit the options for that entry.  *Double click on an entry to disable or enable that entry, on WB3+ systems, the entry will appear ghosted when disabled.  The name of an entry can contain wildcards, ModePro supports all @{"AmigaDOS wildcards" link wildcards}. When using wildcards remember that the lists are scanned in the order of Screen Names, Program Names, and ScreenModes, each list is scanned from top to bottom, so if "#?" is in the list no other entries below it will be checked.
  
    In v4.25 wildcard support was added for the ScreenModes list.  Promoting screen modes using wildcards can be tricky if you are not familiar with the Amiga wildcard system.  I have provided some examples to help:
        NTSC:#?Laced#?     will match   NTSC interlaced screens
        NTSC:~(#?laced#?)  will match   NTSC screens that are not interlaced.
        #?Laced#?          will match   any interlaced screens
        #?HAM#?LACED#?     will match   HAM screens that are interlaced.
        #?HAM~(#?LACED#?)  will match   HAM screens that are not interlaced

@{fg highlight}3. Name Gadget@{fg text}
    This allows you to edit the selected name in the list.  When this gadget is active, the @{b}Up@{ub} and @{b}Down@{ub} Cursor keys will allow you to select another item in the list gadget, pressing @{b}Shift@{ub} and either @{b}Up@{ub} or @{b}Down@{ub} will change the priority of the selected item. 

@{fg highlight}4. New Gadget@{fg text}
    Creates a new entry in the list

@{fg highlight}5. Remove Gadget@{fg text}
    Removes the highlighted entry in the list

@{fg highlight}6. Select Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget will allow you to choose the name for the active entry from a list.  The list will contain either all the open screen names, all of the programs name, a list of screenmodes that are currently available or any open public screens.  The Screenmode list has an entry for each type of monitor that will promote all of the screenmodes of that monitor: ex. "NTSC:All".  
 

@{fg highlight}7. Priority Slider Gadget@{fg text}
    This slider is used to adjust an entries priority
@endnode

@node method "Promotion Method & Dimension Gadgets"
@wordwrap

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Promotion Method & Dimension Gadgets@{ub}@{fg text}

 @{fg highlight}1 @{fg text}[G|  Promotion Method       ]   
 @{fg highlight}2 @{fg text}[   Select Screen Mode...   ]   
 @{fg highlight}3 @{fg text}[   Screen Mode Display     ]   
 @{fg highlight}4 @{fg text}Overscan: [G|  xxxx Size    ]   
 @{fg highlight}5 @{fg text}Width:[    ]   Height: [    ] @{fg highlight}6@{fg text} 
 @{fg highlight}7 @{fg text}[/] Colors:    [####        ] @{fg highlight}8@{fg text}  
 @{fg highlight}9 @{fg text}[/] Palette    [   Edit...  ] @{fg highlight}10@{fg text}
@{jleft}
@{fg highlight}1. Promotion Cycle Gadget@{fg text}
    This Gadget has the four following values:
(When the Public Screens list is active, only the latter two options are available) 
@{b}· None@{plain}
    This option is useful in the case that you may not want the dimensions, screenmode, or overscan changed but would like a 3D or autoscrolling screen.
@{b}· Monitor Type@{plain}
    This option promotes a screen to an equivalent resolution under another monitor type specified in the text gadget,  therefore you can promote an NTSC screen to say...an equivalent EURO36 screen, making interlaced screens more bearable.  ModePro    
@{b}· Screen Mode@{plain}
    When ModePro promotes a screen with this option it will promote it with the specific screen type listed in the text gadget.  You may also set the width height and overscan of the screen but the number of colors will be taken from the program that requested the screen  .Use the @{fg highlight}Select Screen Mode...@{fg text} gadget to select the screen mode of your choice.  Also make sure the display mode can handle the number of colors the application program wants, forcing a program to open a 32 color hires screen on and Old Chip Set or Enhanced Chip Set machine will not work.  If the selected screen mode no longer exists, common on multi-rtg systems, then ModePro will attempt to find a suitable replacement.
@{b}· Requester@{plain}
    When ModePro promotes a screen with this option it will bring up a ScreenMode Requester for you to pick a screen mode.  Use the @{fg highlight}Select Screen Mode...@{fg text} gadget to select the initial values of the screen mode requester when it opens.
    @{b}@{i}Notes:@{ui}@{ub}  If you are using a non-AGA machine you may find that the list of screen modes has been limited, this may be a result of the program asking for a screen depth not available at higher resolutions.
@{b}· Best Mode@{plain}
    This option allows you to specify the width, height, overscan and optionally the depth and monitor, and modePro will attempt pick the best Screen Mode.


@{b}@{i}Warning:@{ui}@{ub}  Some programs can't handle screen sizes other than what is coded into the program, some may work, some may crash, some may put garbage all over the screen.

@{fg highlight}2. Select Screen Mode... Gadget@{fg text}
    Use this gadget to select a screen mode, monitor type, or the default settings for "Requester" promotion.

@{fg highlight}3. Screen Mode Display Gadget@{fg text}
    Simply displays the active screen mode

@{fg highlight}4. Overscan Cycle Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget allows you to specify the overscan type using the last two promotion options.

@{fg highlight}5. Width Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget allows you to specify a width using the last two promotion options

@{fg highlight}6. Height Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget allows you to specify a height using the last two promotion options.
@{b}@{i}Notes:@{plain}  Specifying -1 for either will cause the screen to be opened in that screenmodes standard Width or Height.  Specifying 0 for either will cause the screen to be opened in the dimensions the programs specifies.

@{fg highlight}7. Colors Check Box@{fg text}
    Allows you to specify the depth of the screen.  In order to specify the number of colors, you must set the promotion method to 'Promote Screen Mode' or 'Use Screen Requester'.  Also, this has no affect on HAM, HAM-8 or ExtraHalfBright screens or screens that use a custom(application supplied) bitmap.

@{fg highlight}8. Colors Slider@{fg text}
    This gadget specifies the number of colors on the screen if the Color Check Box is checked, and/or, the number of colors in the palette if the Palette Check Box is checked.

@{fg highlight}9. Palette Check Box@{fg text}
    If this is checked, ModePro will open the screen with a palette specified by you.  The number of colors in the palette is indicated by the Colors Slider.

@{fg highlight}10. Edit Palette Gadget@{fg text}
    When this gadget is clicked, ModeProPrefs will open a screen that contains the Palette Requester.  No palette will be defined until you click the Ok Gadget in the requester at least once after the Palette Check Box has been checked for the first time on a particular entry in the promotion list.

@{"Palette Requester" link preq}
 
@endnode

@node options "Option Gadgets"
@wordwrap

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Option Gadgets@{ub}@{fg text}

 @{fg highlight}1 @{fg text}[/] AutoScroll               
 @{fg highlight}2 @{fg text}[/] Interleave               
 @{fg highlight}3 @{fg text}[/] Behind                   
 @{fg highlight}4 @{fg text}[/] Blank Border             
 @{fg highlight}5 @{fg text}[/] Force Planar             
 @{fg highlight}6 @{fg text}Centering:[G|Both Directions]

@{jleft}
@{fg highlight}1. AutoScroll Check Box@{fg text}
    This option will make a promoted screen AutoScroll.  If a screen was originally set to autoscroll you cannot force it to not autoscroll by leaving the checkbox unchecked.

@{fg highlight}2. Interleave Check Box@{fg text}
    This will open a screen with an interleaved bitmap which will increase graphics speed slightly and reduce the flickering that appears when moving big images on the screen.  This option is available under Workbench 3.0 and above only.
@{b}@{i}Warning:@{plain}  Some programs will not function properly or may crash with this option checked.

@{fg highlight}3. Behind Check Box@{fg text}
    This will make a screen open behind all other screens.

@{fg highlight}4. Blank Border Check Box@{fg text}
    This turns on the Blank(Black) Border option (the unused overscan area is turned black).  Note that if your using a utility that turns on the Blank Border feature globally, ModePro will @{b}not@{ub} turn the option off if you leave this option unset.

@{fg highlight}5. Force Planar Gadget@{fg text}
    This option will force the display memory for the screen to be allocated as bitplanes.  This may be needed to promote some programs which expect the Amiga's standard planar graphics to graphics cards whose displays are generally chunky.

@{fg highlight}6. Center Cycle Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget allows you to center the screen.  
The gadget has three values:
· None              Don't center the screen.
· Horizontally      Center the screen horizontally only.
· Vertically        Center the screen vertically only.
· Both Directions   Center the screen both horizontally & vertically.

This option may not work on all screens.

@endnode

@node fontcont "Font Gadgets"
@wordwrap

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Font Gadgets@{ub}@{fg text}

 @{fg highlight}1 @{fg text}Font:[G|      Program       ]
 @{fg highlight}2 @{fg text}[      Select Font...       ]
 @{fg highlight}3 @{fg text}[                     ][    ]
 @{fg highlight}4 @{fg text}[/] Aspect Correction        
@{jleft}
@{fg highlight}1. Font Cycle Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget selects how the font for a screen is picked, the get has three values:
@{b}· Program@{plain}
    Uses the font that the program specifies.
@{b}· System@{plain}
    Uses the system default specified in the system's Font preferences.
@{b}· Specify@{plain}
    Uses the font specified in the Font Name & Size display gadgets.  Until version 3.0, this option sometimes had strange affects on screens that were promoted with this option.  In version 3.0 any screen that uses this option will have to be closed before you can quit ModePro.

The following gadgets are disabled if the Font Cycle Gadget is not set to @{b}Specify@{ub}.

@{fg highlight}2. Select Font... Gadget@{fg text}
    Opens a font requester so you can choose a font.

@{fg highlight}3. Font Name & Size Display@{fg text}
    Displays the font name & size.

@{fg highlight}4. Aspect Correction Check Box@{fg text}
    Corrects the aspect of a font so that it doesn't appear distorted when appearing on screens of various aspects. However, this may not work with a lot of bitmap fonts. Outline fonts(CG, Type1) should work fine.
@endnode

@node 3dlook "3D-Look Gadgets"
@wordwrap

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}3D-Look Gadgets@{ub}@{fg text}

 @{fg highlight}1 @{fg text}[/] 3d-Look         
 @{fg highlight}2 @{fg text}[/] Default         
   [      Reset     ] @{fg highlight}3@{fg text}
   |                |  
   |                |  
   |       @{fg highlight}4 @{fg text}       |  
   |                ^  
   |________________V  
   [     @{fg highlight}5 @{fg text}    ][ @{fg highlight}6 @{fg text}]  
@{jleft}
@{fg highlight}1. 3-D Look Check Box@{fg text}
    This will give a promoted screen the WB 2+ 3D look.

@{fg highlight}2. Default Check Box@{fg text}
    If this is set ModePro will use the system's ROM Default pen settings.
    WB3.x users will get the settings from Palette Preferences, note that the "4 Color Settings" are used from Palette preferences editor, however, 2 colors screens get the ROM default. 

@{b}@{i}Notes:@{plain}  You cannot force a screen to not have the 3D look by leaving this box unchecked.


@{fg highlight}3. Reset Gadget@{fg text}
    This will set the pen list to their default values.  The default values will be taken from the default Public screen (usually Workbench)

@{fg highlight}4. Pen List@{fg text}
    This displays the pen names and their values

 @{u}Pens                OS      Desc.                                      @{plain}
 Detail              1.x     obsolete
 Block               1.x     obsolete
 Text                2.0     Text on background
 Shine               2.0     Bright edge on 3d objects(gadgets,windows...)
 Shadow              2.0     Dark edge on 3d objects
 Fill                2.0     Active window border/Selected gadget fill
 Fill Text           2.0     Text over Fill
 Background          2.0     Background color of unselected gadgets
                               and inactive windows borders
 High Text           2.0     Highlighted text color
 Bar Detail          3.0     Text color in screen title bar
 Bar Block           3.0     Color of screen title bar
 Bar Trim            3.0     Trim under screen title bar

@{fg highlight}5. Current Pen Name Display Gadget@{fg text}
    This displays the current pen name your editing.

@{fg highlight}6. Pen Value Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget allows you to change the value of the selected pen.  Hit Enter to advance to the next pen.  Hitting Tab will also advance to the next pen, but it will also change the active string gadget.  Also, press the @{b}Up@{ub} or @{b}Down@{ub} Cursor keys to select another pen to edit while this gadget is active.  Negative values are acceptable, the pen is selected by subtracting that number from the number of colors on the screen, if you type in -2, and there are 16 colors, then the pen will use color 14.

@endnode


@node backdrop "Backdrop Gadgets"
@wordwrap

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Backdrop Gadgets@{ub}@{fg text}

 1 Backdrop:[G|    None     ]

@{jleft}             
 (V39 only)

@{fg highlight}1. Backdrop:@{fg text}
  This gadget selects the type of backdrop.
    @{b}· None@{ub} - no backdrop
    @{b}· Picture@{ub} - an Image tiled as the background
    @{b}· Color@{ub} - a solid color

With @{b}Picture@{ub} selected, the following gadgets are available...
@{jcenter}
 2 [ File ][       3      ]
 4 [/] Center              
@{jleft}
  
@{fg highlight}2. File Gadget@{fg text}
    Click this gadget to select a picture to display in the backdrop.

@{fg highlight}3. File Display Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget displays the selected file.

@{fg highlight}4. Center@{fg text}
    Instructs ModePro to center the image.

With @{b}Color@{ub} selected, the following gadgets are available...
@{jcenter}
 6       Color         
 [@{bg shade}                    @{bg background}]
@{jleft}
@{fg highlight}6. Backdrop Color Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget displays the background color for the screen.  Clicking on the gadget will allow you to edit the color.  In order for this gadget to work, ModeProPrefs requires that atleast 2 free pens be available on the screen that ModeProPrefs appears on.
    ModePro uses the OS to pick the best available pen to render in, if there are few or none available pens, ModePro may show the wrong color or no color at all.
    If CyberGraphics is available and the screen is true color, ModePro will use CyberGraphics to render the color.
    
@endnode



@node oldbackdrop "Old Backdrop Gadgets"
@wordwrap

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Backdrop Gadgets@{ub}@{fg text}

 @{fg highlight}1 @{fg text}[/] Backdrop     
 @{fg highlight}2 @{fg text}[ File ][   @{fg highlight}3    ] 
 @{fg highlight}4 @{fg text}[/] Center       
@{jleft}             
 (V39 only)

@{fg highlight}1. Backdrop@{fg text}
    This gadget enables the Backdrop options.

@{fg highlight}2. File Gadget@{fg text}
    Click this gadget to select a picture to display in the backdrop.

@{fg highlight}3. File Display Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget displays the selected file.

@{fg highlight}4. Center@{fg text}
    Instructs ModePro to center the image.



@endnode


@node share "Share Pen Gadgets"
@wordwrap

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Share Pen Gadgets@{ub}@{fg text}

 @{fg highlight}1 @{fg text}[/] Share Pens    
 @{fg highlight}2 @{fg text}Exclude:[        ]
@{jleft}             
 (V39 only)

@{fg highlight}1. Share Pens@{fg text}
    This gadget tells ModePro to open the screen using WB3+ shared pen system.  This, along with the Public Screen option, will allow you to open programs like MultiView on these screens and allocate the pens for their use.

@{fg highlight}2. Exclude Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget tells ModePro to exclude certain pens from being shared.  This is useful when, for example, if you have a program that expects certain pens to be certain colors.  Without this option those pens could be modified without the program knowing, which could result in an oddly colored display.

You can specify multiple pen numbers in the gadget by:
@{b}· Separating each pen number by a comma or space or both ( 0,1,2,3 or 0 1 2 3 )@{ub}
@{b}· Specifying a range of numbers using a dash '-' ( 0-3 )@{ub}
@{b}· Or a combination of the two (example 0,1,2, 5-10, 12, 14, 16-18)@{ub}

@{b}@{i}Note:@{plain}  This gadget will only allow you to enter the characters '0' through '9', ' '(space), ','(comma) and '-'(dash).  Entering other characters will make the screen beep.

@{b}@{i}Example:@{ub}@{ui}  If you had a program that opened on a 16 color screen, and you promoted it to 256 color, specified 'shared pens' and the program was not aware of the shared pen system, then you'ld want to exclude pens 0-15, this way, if you popped Multiview up on that screen, Multiview would not destroy the palette of the first 16 colors.
@endnode


@node pubcont "Public Control Gadgets"
@wordwrap

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Public Control Gadgets@{ub}@{fg text}

 @{fg highlight}1 @{fg text}[/] Make Public   
 @{fg highlight}2 @{fg text}Name:[           ]
@{jleft}
@{fg highlight}1. Make Public Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget specifies whether the promoted screen is to be public of not.
 
ModePro closes screens it makes public asynchronous to the application that actually created the screen.  The screen will not be closed until:
@{b}· There are no windows open on the screen.@{ub}
@{b}· The application that opened the screen has called the intuition.library function CloseScreen().@{ub}
    This lets ModePro know the the application is done with the screen, and that it can be safely closed.

@{b}@{i}Note:@{ub}@{ui} You @{b}do not@{ub} need too close all of the 'visitor' windows before you quit the application that opened the screen.  If you quit the application before all the visitor windows are closed, ModePro will close the screen as soon as all of the visitor windows are closed.

In v4.30 the way screen titles are handled has changed, the original title is used until the application closes the screen, if the screen remains open because another program has opened a visitor window, a copy of the original title is used.

Screens that ModePro cannot make public are those that:
@{b}· Have their BitMap memory supplied to them by the application instead of allowing the OS to allocate the BitMap. (mainly paint programs)@{ub}
@{b}· Have already been specified as being public by the application that is opening the screen.@{ub}
@{b}· Require that the program that created the screen remain in memory.@{ub}

@{b}@{i}Node:@{plain}  ModePro cannot be quit until all promoted screens that it has also made public have been closed.
 
@{fg highlight}2. Public Name Gadget@{fg text}
    This is the Public Name of the screen.  ModePro also places the public name of the screen in the title bar instead of the original title. the public name may have a number appended to it, if multiple public screens with the same name are opened. (ex, 'PUBNAME' 'PUBNAME.2' ... ) 

@endnode

@node scrhotkey "Screen Hot Key Gadgets"
@wordwrap

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Screen Hot Key Gadgets@{ub}@{fg text}

 @{fg highlight}1 @{fg text}[/] Screen Hot Key
 @{fg highlight}2 @{fg text}Hot Key:[        ]
@{jleft}
@{fg highlight}1. Screen Hot Key Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget specifies whether the promoted screen is to have a Hot Key that will place the screen in front of all others.

@{fg highlight}2. Hot Key Gadget@{fg text}
    This will be the Hot Key for the screen.

@{i}@{b}Notes:@{plain}  Changing the string in the Hot Key Gadget will not affect any screens that are already open.  If multiple screens are opened the share the same hot key, pressing the hot key will cycle through those screens.  ModePro cannot be quit until all promoted screens that it have this option have be closed.

@{b}@{i}Tip:@{plain}  If you use FKey or a similar program to launch programs,  by setting the @{"CX_PRIORITY" link tooltypes} tooltype of ModePro to a higher value than that of FKey's, you can use one hotkey to start a program with FKey, and then have ModePro pop the screen to the front while that program has its screen open using the same hotkey without FKey running the program again.

@endnode 

@node saveusecancel "Save, Use & Cancel Gadgets"

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Save, Use & Cancel Gadgets@{ub}@{fg text}

@{fg highlight}1 @{fg text}[ Save ]   @{fg highlight}2 @{fg text}[ Use ]   @{fg highlight}3 @{fg text}[ Cancel ]
@{jleft}
@{fg highlight}1. Save Gadget@{fg text}
    Saves the current settings as permanent.

@{fg highlight}2. Use Gadget@{fg text}
    Use the current settings, they will be lost if the system is reset.

@{fg highlight}3. Cancel Gadget@{fg text}
    Restore the settings and exit.
@endnode

@node unknownscreengads "Unknown Screen Gadgets"

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Unknown Screen Gadgets@{ub}@{fg text}

@{fg highlight}1 @{fg text}[    Use   ]   @{fg highlight}2 @{fg text}[ Use & Delete ]   @{fg highlight}3 @{fg text}[ Never Again ]   @{fg highlight}4 @{fg text}[ Cancel ]
@{jleft}
When an unknown screen is requested and the @{"Ask About Unknown Screens" link menus} menu item is check, ModePro will prompt you as to how and if you would like to promote the screen, if you choose to promote the screen, ModeProPrefs will open and the normal @{"Save Use and Cancel" link saveusecancel} gadgets will be replaced with those above.  ModeProPrefs forces you to edit the new entry for the unknown screen and decide whether or not you want to keep or delete the entry.  Note that while ModeProPrefs is in this mode, the @{"Promotion List" link list} gadgets will not be available.  

@{fg highlight}1. Use Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget tells ModePro to keep the new entry and promote the screen.  Note that ModePro doesn't save the new entry to disk until told to do so (by pressing the Save Gadget).

@{fg highlight}2. Use & Delete Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadget tells ModePro to promote the screen and then discard the entry.

@{fg highlight}3. Never Again Gadget@{fg text}
    This gadgets causes ModePro to and an entry to the promotion list the tells ModePro to never ask to promote this screen again.  An entry will be added to a promotion list, however it will be uneditable.

@{fg highlight}4. Cancel Gadget@{fg text}
    This tells ModePro not to promote the screen. Unlike the "Never Again" gadget, if the same is requested again, ModePro will ask if you want to promote it.
@endnode

@node tooltypes "Arguments and ToolTypes"
@wordwrap

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Arguments and ToolTypes@{ub}@{fg text}
@{jcenter}
@{b}MODEPRO@{ub}
@{jleft}  @{b}** The command line has changed in v4.17 **
@{b}Format:@{ub}  MODEPRO [CX_PRIORITY<priority>] [CX_POPKEY<key>] [CX_POPUP<yes|no>] [PREFSCOMMAND<command>] [WBPROMOTABLE] [PATCHLAYOUTMENU<yes|no>] [QUIT] [QUIET] [DEBUG]

@{b}Template:@{ub}  CX_PRIORITY/N/K, CX_POPKEY/K, CX_POPUP/K, PCMD=PREFSCOMMAND/K, WBPROMOTABLE/S, PLM=PATCHLAYOUTMENUS/K, QUIT/S, QUIET/S, DEBUG/S: 


@{b}Purpose:@{ub}  This program contains the system patches and promotion code.

@{b}@{fg highlight}Tooltypes:@{fg text}@{ub}
@{b}CX_POPUP=YES/NO@{ub}
(default YES) (changed from NO in version 3.6)
@{b}CX_POPKEY=<hotkey>@{ub}
  (default lcommand p)
@{b}CX_PRIORITY@{ub}
  (default 0)
@{b}DONOTWAIT@{ub}
@{b}STARTPRI@{ub}
@{b}PREFSCOMMAND=<command>@{ub}
  (default sys:prefs/ModeProPrefs) Command to run ModeProPrefs.
@{b}PATCHLAYOUTMENU=<yes|no>@{ub}
  Installs the LayoutMenu patch if yes (by defualt yes).  If this is set to No, ModePro NewLookMenu patch is disabled.
@{b}WBPROMOTABLE@{ub}
  Normally ModePro will only use certain options for the Workbench screen, this option allows ModePro to use every option for the Workbench screen.  This option should not be used lightly.  See @{"Promoting Workbench" link workbench}
@{b}QUIT@{ub}
  Attempt to quit MP. if MP can't quit, MP will show a requester.  Use QUIET aswell to supress requesters.
    See @{" Promotion Tips & Tricks " link tips}     
@{b}QUIET@{ub}
  Tells MP to not show requesters when attempting to quit, and to not popup.
@{b}DEBUG@{b}
    

@{jcenter}
@{b}MODEPROPREFS@{ub}
@{jleft}
@{b}Format:@{ub}  MODEPROPREFS [FROM<filename>] [EDIT] [USE] [SAVE] [PUBSCREEN=<pubname>] [ENABLEPROMOTION=<yes|no>] [NEWLOOKMENUS=<yes|no>] [ASK_UNKNOWN=<yes|no>] [CENTER_HORZ=<yes|no>] [CENTER_VERT=<yes|no>] [FONT_NAME<font>] [FONT_SIZE<size>] [IMPORT] [DEBUG]

@{b}Template:@{ub}  FROM, EDIT/S, USE/S, SAVE/S, PUBSCREEN/K, PRO=ENABLE_PROMOTION/K, NLM=NEWLOOKMENUS/K, ASK=ASK_UNKNOWN/K, CH=CENTER_HORZ/K, CV=CENTER_VERT/K, FN=FONT_NAME/K, FS=FONT_SIZE/K/N, IMPORT/K, DEBUG/S: 

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}  This program is used to edit the promotion lists and change various options
in ModePro.

@{b}@{fg highlight}Tooltypes:@{fg text}@{ub}
@{b}FROM=<filename>@{ub}
  A preference file to load.
@{b}EDIT@{ub}
  Edit the current settings or the file specified by FROM.
@{b}USE@{ub}
  Use the current settings or the file specified by FROM.
@{b}SAVE@{ub}
  Save the current settings or the file specified by FROM as default.
@{b}PUBSCREEN=<pubname>@{ub}
  Public screen to open the preference editor on.
@{b}ENABLE_PROMOTION=<yes|no>@{ub}
  Turn on or off screen mode promotion.
@{b}NEWLOOKMENUS=<yes|no>@{ub}
  Turn the NewLookMenu patch on or off.
@{b}ASK_UNKNOWN=<yes|no>@{ub}
  Turn on or off the "Unknwon Screen" requester.
@{b}CENTER_HORZ=<yes|no>@{ub}
  Center unknown screens horizontally.
@{b}CENTER_VERT=<yes|no>@{ub}
  Center unknown screens vertically.
@{b}FONT_NAME=<font>@{ub}
  (defaults to the screen font or Topaz) (ex. 'Times.font')
@{b}FONT_SIZE=<size>@{ub}
  (default 8)  Specify the Font to use for ModeProPref's interface.  Ignored if @{b}FONT_NAME@{ub} is not specified.
@{b}IMPORT=<file>@{ub}
  Import promotion settings from another file.  Duplicates are ignored. (4.62)
@{b}DEBUG@{ub}
  Turns on ModePro's debugging output - some versions of ModePro will ignore this option (it's mostly for my own debuging).  If it is available, output is done through the serial port (use sushi). 
  This option also modifies the task names of programs in the patch code so the enforcer hits are easier to trace, this may affect other programs and hacks that expect to find programs with a specific name.
@endnode

@node warning "WARNING!!"

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Warning!@{ub}@{fg text}
@{jleft}
    Use of this program is done at your own risk.  I am not responsible for any damage, injuries or fatalities through the use of this program.

@{b}YOU HAVE BEEN WARNED!@{ub}
@endnode

@node details "Technical Details"

@{jcenter}@{b}@{fg highlight}Technical Details@{ub}@{fg text}
@{jleft}
This program patches the following functions:

@{b}intuition.library@{ub}
@{u}OpenScreen & OpenScreenTagList@{uu} - Patched with ModePro's promotion function which add's and modifies options, and then calls the original OpenScreenTagList function. 
@{u}CloseScreen@{uu} - To free resources ModePro allocates from the patch above(Font, Public Screen, and Hot Key options). It then calls original function.
@{u}OpenWindow & OpenWindowTagList@{uu} - To set the NewLook menu option and for the Public Screen Manager.
@{u}LockPubScreen@{uu} - Patched for ModePro's Public Screen Manager.
@{u}UnlockPubScreen@{uu} - Patched for ModePro's Public Screen Manager. Added 4.53
@{u}CloseWorkbench@{uu} - This had to be patch because this function calls CloseScreen() directly and not thru the LVO.

These two were added in 4.46 but have been removed in 4.53
@{u}LockPubScreenList@{uu}   - Adds ModePro's public screens to the system's Public Screen list, even when the screen isn't open.  This allows applications that normally display a list of open Public Screens, to also display ModePro's as well.
@{u}UnlockPubScreenList@{uu} - Cleans up mess created from above.

@{b}gadtools.library@{ub}
@{u}LayoutMenu@{uu} - patched to set the NewLook menu option.

These patches can be safely removed as long as no other program patches the functions after this program does.  If another program has patched over ModePro's patches, the ModePro will not allow you to quit. The code that removes these patches in 3.0, is considerably better than before, previous versions left themselves open for attack for a short period of time.

@endnode

